A sterilization process that uses nitrogen dioxide to kill microorganisms.
A sterilization process that uses supercritical carbon dioxide to kill microorganisms.

This gene plays a role in both the ubiquitination and phosphorylation of proteins.

Human DCAF1 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 3p21.2 and is approximately 110 kb in length. This allele, which encodes DDB1- and CUL4-associated factor 1 protein, is involved in both substrate recognition by the E3 ubiquitin-protein ligase complex and serine-threonine phosphorylation.

DDB1- and CUL4-associated factor 1 (1507 aa, ~169 kDa) is encoded by the human DCAF1 gene. This protein plays a role in both serine/threonine-protein kinase activity and E3 ubiquitin-protein ligase complex substrate recognition.
This gene is involved in protein ubiquitination.

A publically-accessible database derived from the Social Security Administration's (SSA) Death Master File Extract. It includes a listing of the vital statistics of a majority of decedents reported to the SSA since 1962.

Human MAGEB2 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of Xp21.3 and is approximately 5 kb in length. This allele, which encodes melanoma-associated antigen B2 protein, plays a role in regulating ubiquitin ligase activity.
A published record of a person's death that usually includes a brief biography and details of the funeral arrangements.
The lysine residue found at amino acid position 4 in the histone H3 protein. Methylation of this residue may be a marker for transcriptionally active genes.
Melanoma-associated antigen B2 (319 aa, ~35 kDa) is encoded by the human MAGEB2 gene. This protein is involved in enhancing ubiquitin ligase activity.
The lysine residue found at amino acid position 9 in the histone H3 protein. Methylation of this residue may be a marker for transcriptionally repressed genes.

A human antibody which recognizes ricin epitopes. These antibodies often develop in response to treatment with immunotoxins that are comprised of ricin immunoconjugates and limit the effectiveness of the treatment.
The density of vessels with an internal diameter greater than 100 microns. Changes in density can occur in or near tumors.
A process that results in the breaking of macromolecular DNA into small pieces.
A family of phosphodiesterases that hydrolyze cyclic AMP to form AMP. This enzyme family is the primary cyclic nucleotide phosphodiesterase expressed by immune cells.
A natural number greater than twenty and less than twenty-two and the quantity that it denotes.
